The majority only found very modest success in the market, if any success at all.
Additionally, Burr wasn't an overly active trader, averaging 3.2 stock sale transactions per quarter over the past eight years.
Kevin Fahey, a lecturer at Swansea University who reviewed Sacerdote's findings, told NPR, "Lawmakers are not making money off of their [stock market] decisions.
Maybe Richard Burr made money ... but all senators taken as a whole, all lawmakers don't seem to be doing this systematically."
